         <abstract>
            <p>Suppose that the (not identically zero) linear operator A, on a real Hilbert space H to itself, is compact, selfadjoint, and positive semidefinite; that y is a vector of H which is perpendicular to the null space of A; and that μ is a real number such that &lt;latex&gt;$0 &lt; \mu &lt; 2/\|A\|$&lt;/latex&gt;. Then, the "iteration scheme" x&lt;sub&gt;n+1&lt;/sub&gt; = x&lt;sub&gt;n&lt;/sub&gt; + μ(y - Ax&lt;sub&gt;n&lt;/sub&gt;), n = 0, 1, 2, ⋯, yields a strongly convergent sequence of vectors {x&lt;sub&gt;n&lt;/sub&gt;}&lt;sup&gt;∞&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;sub&gt;n=0&lt;/sub&gt; if and only if "Picard's criterion" for the existence of a solution of Ax = y holds (i.e., if and only if y is perpendicular to the null space of A, and &lt;latex&gt;$\sum^\infty_{k=1}(y, u_k)^2/\lambda^2_k &lt; \infty$&lt;/latex&gt;, where the u&lt;sub&gt;k&lt;/sub&gt; and the λ&lt;sub&gt;k&lt;/sub&gt; are the orthonormalized eigenvectors, and the corresponding eigenvalues, of A, respectively). An analogous result holds when A is only required to be compact.</p>
          </abstract>
